{
  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara* (The Call of the Marching Bell) contains several poems that directly address or personify natural objects through apostrophe, dialogue, or vivid personification, treating them as interlocutors. Here are the relevant ones matching your specified objects:**\n\n### Mountain\n- **Himalaya** (*Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 25): Directly apostrophized multiple times as \"O Himalaya,\" praising its majesty, eternity, and role as India's sentinel.[^1]\n- **Ek Pahar aur Gilehri** (A Mountain and a Squirrel, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 21): A dialogue where the mountain haughtily addresses the squirrel, boasting of its size, only to be humbled.[^2]\n\n### Sun\n- **Aaftab** (The Sun, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 14): Opens with \"O Sun!\" hailing it as the soul of the world, source of life, and eternal light.[^3]\n\n### River\n- **Kinaar-e-Ravi** (On the Banks of the Ravi, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 28): Contemplatively addresses the Ravi River (\"The Ravi, lost in song\"), evoking its music and the transience of life by its flow.[^4]\n\n### Wave\n- **Mauj-e-Darya** (The Wave, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 31): The wave speaks in first person of its restless torment and yearning for the ocean, embodying dynamic nature.[^5]\n\n### Moon\n- **Chaand** (The Moon, *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 3): Directly addressed as \"O Moon,\" sharing a quest for beauty and light hidden in earthly life.[^6]\n- **Maah-e-Nau** (The New Moon, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 30): Addresses the crescent as \"O planet,\" likening it to a fragment of the sun and yearning to follow its journey.[^7]\n\nNo other Iqbal works in the corpus (only *Bang-e-Dara* Parts 1–3) feature direct addresses to these exact objects. Searches for phrases like \"O river\" or \"O wave\" yielded no additional matches, though nature motifs abound elsewhere.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Himalaya,\" [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-b8c905).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Ek Pahar aur Gilehri,\" [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/21-ek-pahar-aur-gilehri/translation/#p-a2b453).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Aaftab,\" [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/14-aaftab/translation/#p-96b3da).\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Kinaar-e-Ravi,\" [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/28-kinaar-e-ravi/translation/#p-70a0dc).\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Mauj_e_Darya,\" [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/31-mauj-e-darya/translation/#p-475086).\n[^6]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, \"Chaand,\" [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/03-chaand/translation/#p-ed353d).\n[^7]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Maah-e-Nau,\" [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/30-maah-e-nau/translation/#p-bb533d).",
